I now have a complete understanding of the codebase. Here is the full implementation plan.

---

## Implementation Plan: `mistral-instruct-v3` Handler

### Overview

This plan adds a new specialized chat template handler for Mistral Instruct v3 models to `common/chat.cpp`. Unlike all existing handlers, this one manually constructs the prompt string by iterating over messages rather than delegating to `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl()`. The handler uses the classic Mistral Instruct v1/v2/v3 format: `[INST]`/`[/INST]` delimiters with `<s>`/`</s>` BOS/EOS tokens.

### Change 1: Insert the handler function

**File:** `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775384599629-i8y586/common/chat.cpp`

**Location:** Between the closing `}` of the `workaround` namespace (line 1622) and the `common_chat_extra_context()` function (line 1624). Insert the new function at line 1623, i.e., between lines 1622 and 1624.

**Rationale:** All existing handler functions (`common_chat_params_init_ministral_3`, `common_chat_params_init_gpt_oss`, etc.) are defined as `static` functions at file scope before the dispatch function. The `workaround` namespace ends at line 1622 and the next file-scope static function (`common_chat_extra_context`) begins at line 1624. Placing the new handler between them maintains the pattern that all handlers are defined before the dispatch function.

**Exact code to insert after line 1622:**

```cpp

static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;
    data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY;

    std::ostringstream prompt;
    std::string system_content;
    bool first_user = true;

    for (const auto & msg : inputs.messages) {
        std::string role    = msg.value("role", "");
        std::string content = msg.value("content", "");

        if (role == "system") {
            system_content = content;
            continue;
        }

        if (role == "user") {
            if (first_user) {
                prompt << "<s>[INST] ";
                if (!system_content.empty()) {
                    prompt << system_content << "\n";
                }
                prompt << content << " [/INST]";
                first_user = false;
            } else {
                prompt << "[INST] " << content << " [/INST]";
            }
        } else if (role == "assistant") {
            prompt << content << "</s>";
        }
    }

    data.prompt = prompt.str();
    return data;
}
```

**Key design decisions:**

1. **Manual prompt building:** The requirements explicitly state this handler should NOT use `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl`. Instead it iterates `inputs.messages` (a `nlohmann::json` array) using `msg.value("role", "")` and `msg.value("content", "")` for safe field access.

