# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Specialized Chat Template Handler

## Context

Mistral Instruct v0.3 models (e.g., Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3) use a classic `[INST]`/`[/INST]` chat format that differs from the newer Ministral 3 format (which uses `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, `[TOOL_CALLS]`, `[ARGS]`). This change adds a dedicated handler so llama.cpp can natively support the v0.3 instruction format without relying on Jinja template rendering.

## Files Modified

- **`common/chat.cpp`** — two insertions (handler function + detection block)
- No changes to `common/chat.h` or any other file

## Step 1: Add handler function in `common/chat.cpp`

**Insert after line 1622** (the closing `}` of the `workaround` namespace) and **before line 1624** (`static json common_chat_extra_context()`).

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;
    data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY;

    std::ostringstream prompt;
    std::string system_content;
    bool first_user = true;

    for (const auto & msg : inputs.messages) {
        std::string role    = msg.value("role", "");
        std::string content = msg.value("content", "");

        if (role == "system") {
            system_content = content;
            continue;
        }

        if (role == "user") {
            if (first_user) {
                prompt << "<s>[INST] ";
                if (!system_content.empty()) {
                    prompt << system_content << "\n";
                }
                prompt << content << " [/INST]";
                first_user = false;
            } else {
                prompt << "[INST] " << content << " [/INST]";
            }
        } else if (role == "assistant") {
            prompt << " " << content << "</s>";
        }
    }

    data.prompt = prompt.str();
    return data;
}
```

**Key design points:**
- Manually builds prompt by iterating `inputs.messages` (does NOT use `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl`)
- Uses `msg.value("role", "")` and `msg.value("content", "")` for safe JSON field access
- System message is captured and prepended to the first user message (separated by `\n`)
- `<s>` only appears once at the start of the first `[INST]` block
- Assistant content is followed by `</s>`
- Uses `std::ostringstream` (already `#include <sstream>` at line 25)
- Format: `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY` — no grammar, no tool support, no PEG parsing

**Example outputs:**
- With system: `<s>[INST] You are helpful.\nhello [/INST] assistant1</s>[INST] user2 [/INST]`
- Without system: `<s>[INST] hello [/INST] assistant1</s>[INST] user2 [/INST]`

## Step 2: Add detection block in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`

**Insert after line 1688** (end of GigaChatV3 block) and **before line 1690** (`return std::nullopt;`). Note: after Step 1's insertion, these line numbers will have shifted by ~40 lines, so target the anchor text `return std::nullopt;` at the end of the function.

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v3 - classic [INST]/[/INST] format without [SYSTEM_PROMPT]
    if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos && src.find("[/INST]") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

**Ordering rationale:** Placed last (just before `return std::nullopt`) because `[INST]`/`[/INST]` are generic markers. The absence-of-`[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` check prevents collision with the Ministral 3 handler (which checks for `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` at line 1640). Placing it after all other checks provides belt-and-suspenders safety.

## Verification

